  "prompt": "Who are all the countries in debt to?",
  "response": "Countries can incur debt in a variety of ways, often borrowing from several sources to fund their obligations. These sources include:\n\n1. **Other Countries**: Bilateral loans between governments. For example, China has become a significant lender to many developing countries through its Belt and Road Initiative.\n\n2. **International Organizations**: Multilateral institutions such as the International Monetary Fund (IMF), World Bank, and regional development banks like the Asian Development Bank (ADB) and African Development Bank (AfDB).\n\n3. **Private Creditors**: Countries can borrow from commercial banks, investment funds, and other private-sector entities.\n\n4. **Bond Market**: Governments issue sovereign bonds that are sold to investors worldwide. These investors could be individuals, corporations, financial institutions, or foreign governments.\n\n5. **Domestic Sources**: Governments might also borrow from domestic sources, including banks, pension funds, and other financial institutions within their own country, as well as from citizens buying government bonds.\n\nThe exact breakdown of debtors and creditors varies significantly from country to country based on their borrowing strategies, economic status, and historical relationships with lenders.",
